Which of the following is an unusual permission field for a UNIX file:

    -rwx---r-x
    (It is very unusual to grant read and execute permissions to "others" / the general public, while completely denying those same permissions to the file's "group").

When a program is started:

    A copy of it is made in a volatile medium.
    (The executable file is copied from the non-volatile disk into volatile RAM).

This program: function f() { f(); } f();

    Runs time-sliced until it crashes by running out of stack space.
    (This is an infinite recursion. It won't freeze the whole system because of time-slicing, but it will eventually consume its allocated stack memory and crash with a Stack Overflow).

Linux dominates supercomputers and other specialist computer niches because:

    Open source Linux can be customised to unusual hardware.

One of the following file protections will break your web page:

    -rwxr-x--x
    (The last three characters --x mean that "others/world" only have execute permissions, but no read permissions. A web server runs as an "other" user and needs read access to serve an HTML file).

What is wrong with this command? wget -O - [https://biscuits.com/biscuit.jpg](https://biscuits.com/biscuit.jpg)

    The JPEG should be saved into a file.
    (The -O - flag tells wget to output the downloaded file directly to standard output/the terminal. Spitting raw binary image data into the terminal will garble the screen).

What command will search all your files for lines containing start of line, then any number of spaces, then the string "born"?

    grep "^ *born" *
    (^ means start of line,  * means a space repeated zero or more times, and born is the literal string).

If a program is not in the directories listed in the "PATH" environment variable:

    It can be run by typing its absolute file path.
    (Or its relative path, such as /home/user/myprogram or ./myprogram).

On Linux, when you type a normal command, it should be in the PATH to run. Yet when you run ps -f you see a program running that is not in the PATH. How can this happen?

    You can run programs that are not in the PATH.

Compile-time binding works only on a:

    Single user, single process system.
    (Compile-time binding hardcodes exact physical memory addresses into the executable. If multiple processes ran at once, they would try to use the exact same memory locations and crash).

As a result of the "unused RAM is wasted RAM" idea, we may:

    Keep data from terminated processes in memory. And pre-load processes that may be run later.

In my Shakespeare directory, you want to count on how many lines the string "King" appears in Shakespeare. Which of the following will answer that question?

    grep King */act* | wc -l
    (grep outputs every line matching "King", and piping it to wc -l counts the total number of those matching lines across all files).

What will this Shell script do? for i in * \n do \n rm i \n done

    Remove a file called i, perhaps multiple times.
    (Because the script says rm i instead of rm $i, it does not evaluate the variable. It literally tries to delete a file named the letter "i" for every file in the directory).

One of these is true.

    A command-line system is easier to automate than a GUI system.

This command: sed -e 's|<|\&lt;|g'

    is displaying the start of HTML tags but not getting them interpreted.
    (It converts the < character into the HTML entity &lt;, which forces a web browser to display it as literal text rather than interpreting it as code).

If we have to remove a page from memory, what do we do?

    Sometimes write it to disk, sometimes discard it completely.
    (If the page was modified (dirty), it must be saved to the disk. If it is read-only code that hasn't changed, it can just be discarded since a copy already exists on the hard drive).

A user tries to start a program on a single-user, multiple-process system. Why is it not practical for the OS to say to the user: "I'm sorry, another program is occupying memory space 7000-8000. Please terminate the other program before running your program"

    The user will not understand this message.

I am in the directory /stuff/and/things and I type: cd ../../../more/things - What directory am I in now?

    /more/things
    (The first .. goes to and, the second to stuff, the third to the root /. Then it goes into /more/things).

The commands "cd" followed by "cd public_html" followed by "mkdir ../stuff" make a directory called:

    $HOME/stuff
    (Typing cd by itself takes you to $HOME. Then you go into public_html. Making a directory in .. (the parent directory) puts it back in $HOME).

What is this script doing? grep string file > /dev/null \n if test "$?" = "0"

    Testing whether or not the string occurs in the file, without listing the lines on which it does.
    (The > /dev/null part throws away the visible output, and $? checks the exit code of grep to see if a match was quietly found).

Only one of the following makes any kind of sense as a possible permission field for a UNIX file. Which one?

    -r--------
    (This gives the owner read access and gives nobody else any access. This is a standard and sensible permission for sensitive files like private SSH keys).

Typing the command man man > man does what?

    Stores the manual page for "man" in a file with a terrible filename.

What will this shell script do? ls$1

    Probably fail unless arguments are blank.
    (If you pass an argument like -l, the script evaluates as ls-l without a space, which will result in a "command not found" error. If $1 is blank, it just evaluates as ls, which works).

On a multi-user system, when one user's program divides by zero:

    An interrupt is generated and the program is terminated.

We are searching for text in chapters of a book, called names like chap17.html. One of these is definitely not right:

    grep Scotland \*chap*html
    (The backslash escapes the first star, meaning the shell will literally look for a file whose name begins with an asterisk character, rather than treating it as a wildcard).
